hat can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":2,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":33,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":58,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":71,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":80,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel de Aubigny was born in 1257, in Clifton, Lancashire, England, her father, de Aubigny, was 18 and her mother, Matilda De Hiliary, was 17. She married Sir Gilbert de Clifton in 1278, in Clifton, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1257–":"1257–Surnud","1257–Female":"1257–Surnud","1242–1323":"1242–1323","1279–1329":"1279–1329","1279–Male":"1279–Surnud","1281–Male":"1281–Surnud","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1240–1259":"1240–1259","about 1281":"umbes 1281","1242":"1242","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1257":"1257","1279":"1279","1323":"1323","1278":"1278","1453":"1453","about 1279":"umbes 1279","1329":"1329","about 1285":"umbes 1285","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Clifton, Lancashire, England":"Clifton, Lancashire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1257–":"1257–Kuollut","1257–Female":"1257–Kuollut","1242–1323":"1242–1323","